snippet.textDisplay: Well, I guess I'll be that internet guy you spoke of, Rob, but I think fuel tanks have a baffle with a trap door or just a low spot to collect the last of the fuel.  To me, making a fuel tank with a low spot seems best.  You didn't show his baffle well, but without a trap door, it would seem once the fuel level gets below the baffle, you're actually losing the majority of the tank (edit: maybe there are holes in the baffle, I couldn't tell.  If so, ignore this).  You'll draw fuel out of the small baffled section, while all the rest will be full of fuel and blocked by the baffle.  Hopefully there was a one way door in there.  Otherwise, you just reduced the effective capacity of your new tank.  You can fit the fuel in, but it can't reach the pump.
snippet.textOriginal: Well, I guess I'll be that internet guy you spoke of, Rob, but I think fuel tanks have a baffle with a trap door or just a low spot to collect the last of the fuel.  To me, making a fuel tank with a low spot seems best.  You didn't show his baffle well, but without a trap door, it would seem once the fuel level gets below the baffle, you're actually losing the majority of the tank (edit: maybe there are holes in the baffle, I couldn't tell.  If so, ignore this).  You'll draw fuel out of the small baffled section, while all the rest will be full of fuel and blocked by the baffle.  Hopefully there was a one way door in there.
